    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1841-01-31_page01.jpg"/>
                <opener>
                        
                    <salute>
                       
                    </salute>
                </opener>
                <p><note>21</note>
                    I wrote on Saturday to <hi rend="underline">the house<lb/>
                    keeper</hi> at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Grove-House-Kensington-Gore_ENK">Grove house</placeName> to inquire<lb/>
                    whether <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WhitE1"><choice><orig>Lady E W</orig><reg>Lady Elizabeth Whitbread</reg></choice></persName>was expected<lb/>
                    and <hi rend="underline">when</hi> for I was quite tired of<lb/>
                    fruitless inquiries from neighbours<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MarcJ1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> . Marcet</persName> <add>referred me to M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> .Villan</add> and M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Villan &amp; Lady<lb/>
                    <unclear>Theresa Lyles</unclear> and all so near <del>Lady</del><lb/>
                    <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Grove-House-Kensington-Gore_ENK">Grove house</placeName> knew no more than<lb/>
                    the man on the moon - Next door<lb/>
                    neighbors here know nothing of<lb/>
                    one another unless the Houses have<lb/>
                    been introduced to each other regularly<lb/>
                    My note arrived just the very<lb/>
                    day that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WhitE1"><choice><orig>Lady E W</orig><reg>Lady Elizabeth Whitbread</reg></choice></persName> and Miss Grant<lb/>
                    returned &amp; yesterday A servant brought<lb/>
                    a note from <persName ref="./Personography.xml#GranX2">miss Grant</persName> saying that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WhitE1"><choice><orig>Lady E</orig><reg>Lady Elizabeth</reg></choice></persName><lb/>
                    had a dreadful cold &amp; could not stir<lb/>
                    after her journey - longed to see me<lb/>
                    So I could not let that warm heart<lb/>
                    long for me in vain &amp; I answered that<lb/>
                    snow permitting I would be at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Grove-House-Kensington-Gore_ENK">Grove<lb/>
                    house</placeName> between 3 &amp; 4 to day -<lb/>
                    Snow does not seem to know whe<lb/>
                    ther it will permit or not for it<lb/>
                    has been showering scant feathers<lb/>
                    all morning &amp; yet not coming fairly<lb/>
                    to snowing - I have ordered horses for 2<lb/>
                    o clock &amp; then as may be after luncheon<lb/>
                    I had asked <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeR2">Rosa</persName> to accompany<lb/>
                    me and take drive in park after<lb/>
                    But Dentist and tooth ache poor<lb/>
                    body &amp; soul interfere &amp; she <unclear>past</unclear> now<lb/>
                    <unclear>annim</unclear> - sorry - cant -<lb/>
                    I forgot to mention the evening<lb/>
                    party at <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MarcJ1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> . Marcets</persName> to which I<lb/>
                    went the evening after <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauH1">Honora</persName><lb/>
                    left<lb/>
                    
                    <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1841-01-31_page02.jpg"/>
                    <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#London_ENK">London</placeName> &amp; to which she was to have<lb/>
                    gone &amp; <unclear>even one proved</unclear> me to make<lb/>
                    her apologies - I did so and <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MarcJ1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> <lb/>
                    Marcet</persName> was and <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RomiS2">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> . E Romilly</persName><lb/>
                    since she was very sorry - and for<lb/>
                    the cause - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MarcJ1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> . Marcet</persName> has the most<lb/>
                    lively &amp; pert notions about <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SneyM1">Aunt<lb/>
                    Mary</persName> &amp; about you<lb/>
                    The party was rather blue<lb/>
                    but true blue <del>and</del> <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LyelC1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> . Lyell</persName> and<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LyelM1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> . Lyell nee Horner</persName> - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MilmH1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi></persName> and <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MilmM1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> <choice> 
                    <orig>Mil-<lb/>
                    -man</orig>
                    <reg>Milman</reg>
                    </choice><lb/>
                    </persName> nee I dont know who - but whoever<lb/>
                    she was is a very fine woman - and said<lb/>
                    she knew me but I did not know her<lb/>
                    from Abraham - A great deal of agreeable<lb/>
                    conversation with <persName ref="./Personography.xml#LyelC1">Lyell</persName> about whom<lb/>
                    I had luckily just been reading in<lb/>
                    <title ref="./Workography.xml#Patch1" cert="medium">Hall's Patchwork</title> and knew all how<lb/>
                    to ask for further information<lb/>
                    &amp; it was not I only ask for informa<lb/>
                    tion sake totally d-me if I care<lb/>
                    Quite the contrary - and he saw<lb/>
                    that and gave me plainly most <unclear></unclear><lb/>
                    Lord Lansdowne so terribly <unclear></unclear> in<lb/> 
                    person I didn't know him<lb/>
                    but as kind as ever to little me<lb/>
                    M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MilmH1">Milman</persName> black &amp; grey -<lb/>
                    square and solemn stood &amp; stared<lb/>
                    at me but I never got to the speech<lb/>
                    of him &amp; did care much - <unclear>Hinton</unclear><lb/>
                    of the Jews &amp; all I could do without<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BabbC1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Babbage</persName> white as tallow can<lb/>
                    dle as ever, was there - not a abit<lb/>
                    more burnt out than he was 10 years<lb/>
                    ago - but quite an odious to look<lb/>
                    at - touching! how horrible that must be<lb/>
                    - He said graciously to me - but<lb/>
                    forgot I had ever seen his magnum <hi rend="underline">opus</hi><lb/>
                    till I reminded him of his own explanations<lb/>
                    
                    <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1841-01-31_page03.jpg"/>
                    - He gave me cards of admittance<lb/>
                    to his Wednesday &amp; Saturday <note>21</note><lb/>
                    <unclear>service</unclear> for which I thanked him<lb/>
                    sincerely but sincerely determined<lb/>
                    never to use for what should I<lb/>
                    do on that galere - in that are<lb/>
                    na of all the show beasts and<lb/>
                    their worshippers &amp; feeders<lb/>
                    and bear leaders - Lady Morgan<lb/>
                    &amp; all! and all quarrelling<lb/>
                    - if I had time or it were at<lb/>
                    all worth while I could tell you<lb/>
                    of such fights between <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MorgS1">Lady Morgan</persName><lb/>
                    and Lover - between <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SaleX1"><choice> 
                    <orig>Countess<lb/>
                    de Sales</orig>
                    <reg>Countess de Sales</reg>
                    </choice>
                    </persName>
                    and <persName ref="./Personography.xml#StepC1">Lady Stepney</persName><lb/>
                    The <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SaleX1">Countess</persName> having turned <persName ref="./Personography.xml#StepC1"><choice> 
                    <orig>Lady<lb/>
                    S</orig>
                     <reg>Lady Stepney</reg>
                    </choice>
                    </persName>
                    out of her house when she came<lb/>
                    by mistake-on-purpose to a grand<lb/>
                    dinner having been asked only to tea<lb/>
                    I think Honora knows this anec<lb/>
                    dote and may amuse you with it<lb/>
                    tell her that I asked the <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SaleX1">Countess</persName><lb/>
                    about it - and she said true I turned<lb/>
                    her out and <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SmitA2">Abel Smith</persName> pronounced<lb/>
                    " as great an instance as I have heard<lb/>
                    of moral courage in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#London_ENK">London</placeName> this<lb/>
                    many a day<lb/>
                    It was not true that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SaleX1">Madame de S</persName><lb/>
                    had made or intended 2 dinners<lb/>
                    on succeeding days - one for fine<lb/>
                    &amp; the next of scraps for second sale<lb/>
                    She said I c<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> not have been guilty<lb/>
                    of such meanness - I never invited<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#StepC1">Lady S</persName> to dinner at all - only to <unclear>Sod</unclear><lb/>
                    Whenever you come to work<lb/>
                    
                    <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1841-01-31_page04.jpg"/>
                    have the support of feeling how<lb/>
                    completely she fulfilled all<lb/>
                    that she desired all that she<lb/>
                    undertook for <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SneyM1">aunt Mary</persName> &amp;<lb/>
                    supplied that place which none<lb/>
                    else could have supplied<lb/>
                    <hi rend="underline">supplied</hi> without <hi rend="underline">supplanting</hi><lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeL1">Lucy</persName> must have many inter<lb/>
                    nal sources of satisfaction which<lb/>
                    I trust will soothe her mind<lb/>
                    and support her bodily weakness<lb/>
                    Whenever her mind can turn<lb/>
                    to any other objects I have some<lb/>
                    preparing for her - I have been<lb/>
                    long foreseeing how necessary<lb/>
                    some interesting occupation wch<lb/>
                    presently be to her<lb/>
                    you have much that that is pain<lb/>
                    ful dearest <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">mother</persName> still to go<lb/>
                    through - Thank you for writing<lb/>
                    to me at the first moment as you<lb/>
                    did and what you wrote answered<lb/>
                    the purpose of communicating<lb/>
                    to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF3">Fanny</persName> in the best manner<lb/>
                    what your previous note had<lb/>
                    prepared her to hear<lb/>
                    I will wait to hear again<lb/>
                    from you before I make any<lb/>
                    further observations or proposals<lb/>
                </p>
               
             
            </div>
        </body>
        <back> </back>
